ezrah@panix.com (Ezra Herman) writes:

>TO: wild@access.digex.net


>w>>1. Clipper is an encryption / decryption chip which is or is planned
>w>>   to be used in customer devices of digital telephony systems.

>w>True, but no requirement that the devices be digital.

>My understanding is that although the telephone line need not be 
>digital, the devices incorporating the Clipper chip must be.  The 
>Skipjack algorithm works on a bit stream.  It is not an analog 
>encryption scheme.  The only device I know that currently incorporates 
>the Clipper chip is the AT&T secure phone, and I believe that it works 
>by first compressing the analog voice data, then digitizing it, running 
>it through the Skipjack algorithm and then sending it out through a 
>modulator.

>Actually, I'm leaving out some steps- the session key encryption scheme 
>is not specified by Skipjack and I'm not sure how AT&T's doing it.  I 
>understand that it actually can be difficult to get a encrypted link 
>with these phones due to having to go over an analog line.  No doubt 
>they work better over ISDN.

To me, "digital telephony" implies digital circuits such as ISDN. My 
understanding is that Clipper will work fine on analog circuits although 
A/D and D/A circuits are required entering and leaving.

